# Matter

What constitutes a matter? [^a1] Dark matter? Unproven kinds of matter? Let us start with this cool chart:

![The Standard Model of Physics [link](https://quantum.lassp.cornell.edu/lecture/elementary_particle_physics).](../img/blog/50_standard.png)

This chart includes both the matter (i.e., fermions) and force carriers (i.e., bosons). In this section, we will just focus on the fermions: quarks and leptons. According to Claude, the model best summarizes the current state of matter where each element have been rigorously, empirically proven. So, we will just go with this.

Rough notes:

Theoretically speaking, these particles are derived from the framework of quantum mechanics. To understand whether these particles are stochastic or not, we have to interpret the underlying framework of quantum mechanics (which is abstracted).

[^a1]: I swear the more I do this kind of stuff, the more I realized how vague some questions can be. In other words, how chaotic and extremely nuanced our world really is.

